<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
{{Caption|Meshing raw bevel gears}}
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
==Intersection Objects==
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
We have to define the desired cross-sections from their axes outwards, and then revolve them to create objects that will be intersected with the results of the steps above to result in a proper pair of bevel gears.
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
===Revolution Object 1===
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
# Activate the first body ('''Body''').
# Create another [[Image:Sketcher_NewSketch.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_NewSketch|sketch]], and in the sketch:
## Project the lines representing the pitch diameters of our first sketch into our new sketch.
## Draw a construction line from their intersection point to the origin (his is where the pitch cones meet).
## Draw a closed wire of six straight lines:
##* One collinear with the vertical sketch axis,
##* two parallel to the horizontal projection line to define position and thickness of the hub area,
##* two lines perpendicular to the construction line, one running through the intersection point, that define the width of the teeth,
##* one line closing the wire that is only required to run outside the raw bevel gear since it already has a correctly modeled teeth hight.
# Leave the sketch.
# Create another new [[Image:PartDesign_Body.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_Body|PartDesign Body]] ('''Body003''').
# Use a [[Image:PartDesign_SubShapeBinder.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_SubShapeBinder|Sub-Shape Binder]] to copy the sketch into the body.
# Create a [[Image:PartDesign_Revolution.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_Revolution|Revolve]] object ('''Revolution''') from the sub-shape binder.
</div>

[[Image:BevelGears_Example05.png|300px]] [[Image:BevelGears_Example06.png|300px]]

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
{{Caption|Left: Sketch of cross-section.
Right: Resulting Revolution object 1}}
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
===Revolution Object 2===
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
# Activate the first body ('''Body''') again.
# Create another [[Image:Sketcher_NewSketch.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_NewSketch|sketch]], and in the sketch:
## Project the lines representing the pitch diameters, and also the line representing the axis of our smaller bevel gear from our first sketch into our new sketch.
## Draw a construction line from their intersection point of the pitch diameters to the origin.
## Draw a closed wire of six straight lines:
##* One collinear with the projected axis,
##* two parallel to the oblique projected pitch diameter to define position and thickness of the hub area,
##* two lines perpendicular to the construction line, one running through the intersection point, that define the width of the teeth,
##* one line closing the wire that is only required to run outside the raw bevel gear since it already has a correctly modeled teeth hight.
# Leave the sketch.
# Create another new [[Image:PartDesign_Body.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_Body|PartDesign Body]] ('''Body004''')..
# Use a [[Image:PartDesign_SubShapeBinder.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_SubShapeBinder|Sub-Shape Binder]] to copy the sketch into the body.
# Create a [[Image:PartDesign_Revolution.svg|16px]] [[PartDesign_Revolution|Revolve]] object ('''Revolution001''') from the sub-shape binder.
</div>

[[Image:BevelGears_Example07.png|300px]] [[Image:BevelGears_Example08.png|300px]]

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
{{Caption|Left: Sketch of cross-section.
Right: Resulting Revolution object 2}}
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
==Finished Bevel Gears==
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
Now we will intersect the raw bevel gears with the revolution objects to find their common shapes. Having hidden all objects but our raw bevel gears and revolution objects, we will notice that the gears do not protrude enough from the revolution object. Since we built the bevel gears from the tip we can (mis-) use the module value to "scale" the gear and adjust its height before intersecting.
</div>

<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
===Bevel Gear 1===
</div>

